  "Idea": "This paper introduces 'Pragmatic Alignment via Cultural Simulation: A Receiver-Centric Framework for Pre-training Data Generation in Vietnamese Hate Speech Detection'—a paradigm shift from speaker-centric text generation to receiver-informed pragmatic modeling in constructing domain-specific datasets. Rather than focusing solely on how hate speech is produced, our framework models how it is interpreted across diverse sociocultural receptors, capturing the subjective, context-dependent nature of perceived toxicity. We argue that implicit hate often resides not in the utterance itself, but in the interaction between message and recipient—shaped by dialect, identity, age, region, and values. To simulate this, we develop a dual-agent architecture: 'Producer Agents' generate potentially toxic social media content using persona-driven LLMs (as in the original idea), while 'Receiver Agents' simulate interpretation processes grounded in empirically derived sociocultural priors (e.g., sensitivity to gendered language, regional stigma, religious norms). Each Receiver Agent is initialized with psycholinguistic profiles built from survey data and discourse analysis of Vietnamese online communities, enabling differential perception of the same utterance—e.g., a sarcastic comment may be flagged as hostile by a rural older adult but seen as humorous by an urban Gen Z user. The output is a rich dataset of (context, producer utterance, receiver interpretation, emotional valence, action response) tuples, annotated with cultural metadata. These tuples form the basis of a new pre-training objective: Contrastive Pragmatic Alignment (CPA), where the model learns to align utterances with their most likely interpretations across receiver types, using negative sampling from misaligned pairs (e.g., treating a coded slur as neutral when receivers perceive it as highly toxic). This forces the model to internalize cultural nuance rather than rely on lexical patterns alone. The resulting pre-trained model demonstrates superior performance in identifying contextually embedded hate, especially in ambiguous cases involving irony, dog whistles, or indirect aggression. Beyond Vietnamese, this receiver-centric framework offers a scalable method for building culturally aware NLP systems in multilingual, multicultural societies where offensiveness is inherently relational.",
